node.text:
Oral tradition allows art, knowledge, ideas and culture to pass along generations. 
 
Eastern Band of Cherokee Indians stories often contain lessons about solving community problems together and recognizing the contributions of those often overlooked. These stories also contain other practical information if one takes the time to listen and respect the message. 
 
Matthew Tooni, an Eastern Band of Cherokee Indians storyteller and musician, recounts the EBCI story of how disease and medicine came to exist. This tradition continues to be an important way of preserving and passing on information in many cultures even after the advent of paper. 

#NativeAmericanHeritageMonth #IndigenousHeritageMonth #FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque

node.text: Welcome back to Specialist Sunday! Meet Lisa Nagurny, who is the supervisory ranger for resource education in Cades Cove. She supervises rangers at one of the busiest places in the Smokies! Let's get to know Lisa and find out more about her job.

node.text: Welcome back to Specialist Sunday! This week, we are highlighting Jim Renfro, who is Great Smoky Mountain's Air Quality Specialist. Throughout 35 years of Jim's career in the Smokies, he has plenty of insider knowledge to share with us. Check it out!

node.text:
Escape to the Smokies with this video, a morning with the elk in the Oconaluftee river valley. Take some time to Explore this and the new content on https://smokieees.org, we hope it Entertains you! This website is for anyone who wants to learn more about the Smokies and is filled with new opportunities to experience the three E’s: Explore, Entertain and Escape. 
A special thanks to our park partners for their help in creating this new way to share the Smokies! Great Smoky Mountains Institute at Tremont, Discover Life in America, Friends of Great Smoky Mountains National Park, and Great Smoky Mountains Association.

node.title: A Morning with the Oconaluftee Elk

node.text:
Take 2 minutes to watch this video with tips & reminders on how to stay #SmokiesSafe on your next visit! #RecreateResponsibly

For information on road, trail, and facility accessibility, please visit: https://www.nps.gov/grsm/planyourvisit/conditions.htm

NPS Video created with the help of @GSMAssoc

node.accessibility_caption: A pair of boots and a hat with a ranger badge.

node.text:
Happy World Ranger Day! 
As you are traveling around the park, be sure to stop and thank a ranger for their hard work! Not only are they tasked with protecting the park and all of its resources, but they also try to ensure everyone has a safe vacation. We appreciate their dedication to this park, its inhabitants, and its visitors. 👏👏👏
Photo: Chalice Keith

node.accessibility_caption: A view from inside the Missionary Baptist Church looking out onto the tombstones in the cemetery.

node.text:
Great Smoky Mountains National Park has many documented cemeteries that are important examples of the park's early landscape. The park’s burial landscapes link the present era with a rich historical legacy. Cemeteries give us a glimpse into the past by providing fascinating insight into past burial customs, religious beliefs, cultural and ethnic influences, community origins and development, and landscape design principles. Cemeteries also bring together the community and remind people with roots in the Smokies of their ancestors. When you walk around the tombstones, you can envision the struggles that many families endured and imagine what life was like for them.
Next time you visit one of the park’s historical burial sites, take in the beauty and peace of your surroundings and try to remind yourself of the hardships many families faced long ago.
Photo: Ann Jordan

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Great Smoky Mountains NP on July 29, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
You may have seen the observation tower at Clingmans Dome before, but did you know the current tower is the third one to stand in that location?

Pictured here is the first known observation tower to stand atop Clingmans Dome. Built by surveyors in the late 1920s, this tower stood until the 1930s when the creation of Great Smoky Mountains National Park brought about the need for a safer, sturdier observation tower for visitors. 

Stay tuned next week to learn about the tower that came next!#ThrowbackThursday

NPS photo, 1929.

node.accessibility_caption: Minnie DeHart Parish, an African American woman, sitting in a chair with her hands crossed at age 110.

node.text:
The African American Experience Project aims to bring more visibility to the history, stories, and lives of African Americans in the Smokies. Today we are remembering the life of Minnie DeHart Parrish of Bryson City. She was a formerly enslaved woman who lived to be at least 110 years old. Ms. DeHart Parrish lived through the Civil War and the threat of the Ku Klux Klan in Bryson City.  On July 23, 1961, an article titled “Minnie Parrish, Over 100, Remembers Civil War Fears” was written in The Asheville Citizen Times. She is still remembered with much affection by some of the older citizens of Bryson City, described in the Swain County Heritage Book as “a much loved lady whose homespun philosophy influenced all who knew her”.
 
Photo Credit: Swain County Genealogical & Historical Center, The Swain County Heritage Book, 1871-1987

node.accessibility_caption: a lush green forest with a brown sign reminding people to be cautious with the burned area. Sight of a concrete bridge pokes through the trees and a lady a her dog enjoy the trail.

node.text:
The Gatlinburg trail is a 2 mile trail that starts at Sugarlands Visitor Center and leads into the edge of Gatlinburg. This is one of our 2 dog-friendly trails making it great for the whole family! Due to the fire in 2016, the area is still recovering so stay on trail and enjoy!
Alternative Text: A lush green forest with a brown sign reminding people to be cautious with the burned area. Sight of a concrete bridge pokes through the trees and a lady a her dog enjoy the trail.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Great Smoky Mountains NP on July 26, 2021. May be an image of tree, sky, nature and mountain.

node.text:
National Parks are great places to gain a fresh perspective and experience a new setting. For some, that is achieved through hiking. Hiking can be therapeutic or a workout, for others it can be a way to foster a meaningful connection with the outdoors. Across all parks, it’s a shared interest among many. 

Great Smoky Mountains National Park has several trails to hike and explore. They are rated in difficulty from easy to moderate to strenuous and offer spectacular scenery. Trails guide visitors through varied terrain, over exposed hills and sometimes in adverse conditions, yet reward those with views like this that make the hike worth the effort. 

Describe a favorite moment you experienced while hiking in the Smokies!

NPS Photo / Niki Heun
Image description: tall spruce-fir trees emerge in the foreground, while distant mountains sweep the horizon.

node.accessibility_caption: A vibrant red salamander on a bed of moss.

node.text:
Welcome to Great Smoky Mountains National Park, the Salamander Capital of the World!

Here we have a Black-Chinned Red Salamander, a subspecies of the Red Salamander. This subspecies is only found in the Great Smoky Mountains, but you may not see it during the day as it tends to be most active during night. If you are out at night, you may spot one of these salamanders crossing trails and roads searching for its next meal, which includes small insects and other amphibians. The bright red coloration of this species is used to deter predators from eating them, and while this species of salamander is not poisonous, its mimicry of other poisonous salamanders has proven successful in preventing it from becoming prey!

Photo Credit: Shannon Welch

node.accessibility_caption: A green vine with leaves in groups of five.

node.text:
Do you know what poison ivy looks like? (Hint: Count the leaves; one of these photos is Virginia creeper, which has five leaflets rather than three.) 
Not only can you find poison ivy in patches on the ground, but it can also grow into large vines that can look a bit like tree branches. However, it is easy to remember the adage, “leaves of three, let them be.” While some people are immune to this irritating plant, others can have harsh reactions to its oily leaves. Be vigilant while outdoors, as you might come across poison ivy throughout the park. 
NPS photos by Rachel Teeter.

node.accessibility_caption: A green vine with leaves in groups of five.
A small plant with leaves in groups of three.
A maple tree with a large vine on it with leaves in groups of three.
Two barn swallows sitting on a chain-link fence in Cades Cove

node.text:
“I like this place and could willingly waste my time in it.” -William Shakespeare.

If you choose to spend your time in the Smokies this summer, remember to look around and enjoy the little things, like these two barn swallows basking in the sun! 

Whether it’s a salamander in a stream, a bird resting on a fence, or a sunray peeking its way through the tree canopy, taking in little moments can make your trip all the better. 

If you need some ideas on where to go in the park to find small or large wonders, please visit https://www.nps.gov/grsm/planyourvisit/hiking.htm.

Photo: Warren Bielenberg

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Great Smoky Mountains NP on July 22, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and standing.

node.text:
You may know that President Franklin D. Roosevelt dedicated Great Smoky Mountains National Park at Newfound Gap on September 2, 1940, but did you know that First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt made her own visit three years earlier?

In April 1937, Mrs. Roosevelt traveled with a friend to Gatlinburg and visited Cades Cove, viewed spring wildflowers with the park’s first superintendent, and ultimately continued on her travels with a scenic drive across Newfound Gap Road.

Though the First Lady’s visit may have been over 80 years ago, her thoughts about the trip ring true for many today, as it’s noted that she regretted only staying for two days!

#ThrowbackThursday

NPS photos.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Great Smoky Mountains NP on July 22, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and standing.
Photo by Great Smoky Mountains NP on July 22, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, standing and outdoors.
Photo by Great Smoky Mountains NP on July 22, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, people standing and outdoors.
Photo by Great Smoky Mountains NP on July 21, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'What is is this? And how does this impact that?'.

node.text:
We are starting our "this, this, and that" challenge. This challenge gives you the chance to help identify flora and fauna species in the park. Also, you can tell us how those species may impact locations in the park. Are you up for the challenge? So, what is this? And how does this impact that? 

NPS Photo

node.accessibility_caption: Two black bears cubs play wrestling in the forest.

node.text:
“Did you hear the news, mom is kicking us out soon!”

Black bear cubs usually stay with their mother for about 18 months before leaving for a life of their own. Bears that have just left their mother are called yearlings! Generally, a cub will realize it is time to leave its mother when she allows male bears to come closer to her, and no longer seems concerned about her cubs. Despite leaving their mother, the cubs won’t reach their full size until they are about five years old.

Photo Credit: Bob Hailey
